    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Trouble With E</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Jerome D Wiesenberg responds to March 23 article on new electronic devices for children; notes problem such devices can cause in schools when students take tests</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>With two or more of those electronic toys (which can handle wireless communications), a well-versed test taker and an unobservant proctor, there will be a lot more doctors, lawyers and engineers passing their  exams, although fraudulently.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>With two or more of those electronic toys (which can handle wireless communications), a well-versed test taker and an unobservant proctor, there will be a lot more doctors, lawyers and engineers passing their  exams, although fraudulently.</p>
        <p>Pray you never have need for their services.</p>
        <p>JEROME D. WIESENBERG  Fresh Meadows, Queens</p>
      </block>
